Wildfires are becoming larger and more frequent in parts of the USA

Wildfires have been increasing in frequency and magnitude across the US in the over the course of the last century. In fact, the NYT reports that the area of land burned by wildfires is approximately double that which would have been burned without anthropogenic climate change (NYT, 2018). Both increases in temperature and decreases in precipitation are shown to increase the risk of large wildfires (EPA, 2022). Additional variables such as soil moisture and snowpack volume and melt timing are shown to impact wildfire risk. Given the correlation between anthropogenic climate change and the number of very large fires, this notebook will analyze the change in wildfire magnitude across U.S. states, with the plan of eventually analyzing how wildfire frequency and magnitude relate to snow variables like snow-water equivalency (SWE). I follow the steps outlined by authors David Shean & Scott Henderson in their Vector Data tutorial from SnowEx Hackweek to load state data.

Citations:

  • Shean, David & Scott Henderson (2021, July 13). Vector Data. SnowEx HackWeek. https://snowex-2021.hackweek.io/tutorials/geospatial/vector.html
  • Pierre-louis, K., & Popovich, N. (2018, November 27). Climate change is fueling wildfires nationwide, New Report warns. The New York Times. https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/11/27/climate/wildfire-global-warming.html
  • U.S. Environmental Protection Agency. (2022). Climate change indicators: Wildfires | US EPA. Climate Change Indicators: Wildfires. https://www.epa.gov/climate-indicators/climate-change-indicators-wildfires
